availability.p: For internal use by the Faclair na Gàidhlig/DASG projects

note.p: The abreviation here looks more like a superscript e than superscript c. However, a mark to the right of this may indicate an attempt to corect e to c and the lenition marker over the superscript letter further suggests that a c was the intended letter as neither in this MS not elsewhere do we get a superscript e with leniton marker.

There is a mark following this word but it is unclear whether it was intended as a letter form or if the mark arose from something else. If it were intended as a letter form it may be a repetition of the vertical tilde over the r in the line below, which would render it meaningless nonetheless.

Green has has deleted "a fir fein" which appears after this. In the present edition, Green's emendation is appears that is may have originated as a gloss to clarify who was meant given that we get "ar sé ridire" in the next line and could be similarly accounted for.

Where an older MS would begin the letters b, l, and h with a serif which appears as a wedge at the top left of the letter form, the scribe here has a long stroke sloping downwards to the left of the letter. In this instance the scribe appears to have written that stroke too early, and also appears to have noted lenition on the initial d here. The final product is the letters dul where l has a long stroke trailing horizontally leftwards from the top of the letter form which, it seems, was the scribe's way of altering the text so as not to have an error appear at this point.

It seems to me that the sense here is similar to the English work "snake" when used as a verb, i.e. implying motion. Here it is understood as something akin to "she snaked a long silken rope down to him," whether the exact meaning is that it was wound down, moved slowly, or was lowered on against the wall as though a snake (or snail in the case of the Gaelic idiom) were moving along it.

There is a mark above the d in this word where it appears that the scribe began to write something but did not complete that mark. Thus, although Greene (1944) writes dho, the present editor does not agree with this reading.
The scribe initally wrote the letter n, then adding the curly descender to render the character a g.

Following "gedh be" there is a b that is scored out. At the beginning of the next line we find "le" and then a "b" with a suspension stroke. It is the present editor's opinion that either this scribe or the exemplar from which he was working wrote a badly-formed "b", and that the "le b-" should be taken as a repetition of "be" in the previous line.
Black (0080504) gives the headword here as fianuis, a word with similar meaning but they are two distinct headwords in eDIL.
Black (0061181) takes this as dibh-fhearg, unlike this edition which takes it as díberg.
Black (0020671) notes the headword here as annslabhra but the present editor reads it as a form of airlabrae.
Black (0091156) take this as a form of the copula whereas here it is understood to be a form of the substantive verb, attá/tha.
